<P>

</FONT>
</TD>
<TD>
<IMG SRC="http://206.135.232.126/eq/icons/icon1.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="ABSCENTER">
<FONT SIZE="1" color="#000000" face="Verdana, Arial">
posted February 12, 2001 11:58 PM &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
    &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://206.135.232.126/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=edit_post&f=9&t=003747&reply_num=000000&u="><IMG SRC="http://206.135.232.126/eq/edit_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete Post"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://206.135.232.126/cgi-bin/eq/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=reply&f=9&t=003747&replyto=000000"><IMG SRC="http://206.135.232.126/eq/quote_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Reply With Quote"></A>
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<BR>Igbert's Guide to Charm Solo'ing <BR>49th Chanter <BR>Rodcet Nife <P><BR>I successfully solo'ed my enchanter from level 40 to level 49 in a matter <BR>of 4 weeks. <BR>This was basically one weekend day, and 3 or 4 evenings for a few hours per <BR>week. Not a ton of time really. Some people say enchanters are horrible at <BR>solo'ing (I played a rogue to 50, trust me, enchanters are wonderful <BR>soloers). I would even go so far as to say enchanters MAY be the best <BR>solo'ing class around. My backing is that solo'ing is all about damage <BR>output and (avoiding) damage input. For casters damage output is about mana to damage <BR>efficiency. Damage input is almost irrelevant because a casters job (even <BR>in soloing, is to not get hit). Given the right circumstances (which I'll <BR>discuss), the charm spell is the most mana to damage efficient spell in the <BR>game. A charmed 45th level mob puts a mage pet to shame. Especially considering<BR>such a mob can be weilded by (theoretically) an enchanter of 39th level.<P>I've also read the laments of enchanters saying that charm is a death trap. <BR>As I said, I leveled 40 through 49 with almost no grouping and just charm <BR>solo'ing. I died 3 times in that entire time. Once because of linkdeath <BR>(which is incredibly dangerous in a charmed scenario) and the other two <BR>times because my pet hit me and I had a bad string of 3 successive stuns. <BR>Three rounds of combat from my pet was enough to drop my rune and kill <BR>me. <BR>There are two thoughts associated with that. One is, don't let your pet <BR>hit you for 3 rounds  <IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/smile.gif">. And two, despite I'm a pretty wimpy little <BR>enchanter, 3 rounds of combat that can kill me must be doing some very serious <BR>damage. <P>First I'll list the absolute required ingredients for successful charm <BR>solo'ing for me. I'm sure other recipes work, but this is my success list. <BR>I'll then describe some very specific scenarios. <P>1.   SoW. I hate this requirement and that's why I list it first. Mostly <BR>because enchanters don't have it naturally, but despite my disdain, I <BR>cannot see my way around it. Jboots work fine. Enchanters have little <BR>trouble trading clarity to a solo'ing druid for sow and potions aren't <BR>that <BR>expensive. Sad but true - you must be able to outrun your pet. <P>2.   A wide open zone. Along with SoW, you need to be able to run. And <BR>Outrun. You "can" rely on your color-stun spells and charm indoors (getting that <BR>wonderful xp bonus) but that really is just too dangerous. You are <BR>accepting the fact you'll get hit once in awhile. I've gone killing 30 <BR>mobs without getting hit once (even my rune). Outdoor zones are solo'ers dreams. <BR>The zone should also have some dead area where chance of getting jumped is <BR>minimal. Trakanon's teeth is outdoor, but the whole zone is ambush <BR>nightmare. <P>3.   A high-level mob undercon near many normal conning blues. At level 43 <BR>I solo'ed BOTH the kromrif guards in eastern wastes that stand in front of <BR>Kael. My 55th wizard friend lamented he barely had enough mana to do one. I <BR>could do both simultaneously. It was a dance but I could do it. They conned <BR>white or yellow at that time.  I did it, but it was inefficient. Efficiency <BR>is everything, not dramatics. When those two guards fought each other, <BR>they pretty much beat the snot out of each other. Huge hitpoints and huge damage <BR>output. Once my pet won, I'd blast him to kingdom come. This cost me tons <BR>of mana for 2 kills. I learned quickly that by charming one guard, he could <BR>kill 10-15 dire wolves, walrus, snow griffons, giant scouts, etc before <BR>dying. While he was killing, I was medding. I rarely went below 60 mana <BR>until the time he was almost dead and had to zap my former pet dead. Trust <BR>me, this is the key to efficiency - your pet should be very tough and <BR>should kill many, many low blues. As solice to my wizard friend, I could not (and<BR>still cannot) solo one of those guards.. only two  <IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/smile.gif">.<P>4.   The mobs you will kill (and charm) are not casters. Fighting casters <BR>is always a pain. They simply put out too much damage too fast and ignore <BR>your runes. Chanters are all about controlling melee fights. Stick to it. <P><BR>That's really it. That's what you need to get going. Your spells are all <BR>you need after this. <BR>Firstly, I'll describe levels 43-49. I'll describe earlier levels <BR>subsequently, because charming lower lev mobs is easier. It is easier because of one <BR>very important factor. The casting time of Beguile (which works on up to <BR>39th level mobs) is 3.5. The casting time of Cajoling whispers (which works <BR>on up to 45th level mobs) is 4.5. That casting time is incredibly <BR>important. <P>The absolute, number one, most IMPORTANT rule of charming is: <BR>(pardon the caps, but this really is important) <P>DON'T EVER BE NEAR YOUR PET. EVER. <P>(I don't care if he cons amiable, its a lie, he really wants to rip your stinky little <BR>gnomish guts out, eat you, and poop you out tomorrow) <P>The two times I died occurred when my pet unfortunately broke charm in <BR>the 5 seconds per hour that circumstances had me standing by my pet. <P>Simple rule: If your pet is fighting - you are standing OUT of charm/root <BR>spell range medding. You have your pet targeted, your mouse cursor on your <BR>root spell, and your fingers on the CTRL-S keys ready to stand up. <P>If your pet is NOT fighting - you are running with your pet chasing (slowly <BR>losing ground) to your next target. <P>The enchanters that sit medding with a 45th level Frost Giant pet standing <BR>near them are the ones that say charm never lasts and is suicide. <P>By the way ? I did this successful charming episode with 170 INT and 115 <BR>CHA (buffed). Charms lasted anywhere from 6 seconds to 5-6 mins <BR>(estimated). Any charm over 30 seconds is useful. Charm Breaking is not <BR>really a problem. If you aren't ready for it, you die. If you are, its <BR>just the cost of doing business. <P>Ok.. Spell line up from 43-49. <P>1.   Tash <BR>2.   Direct Damage <BR>3.   Root ? (not immoblize, not enstill.. your 8th level Root ? there's a <BR>reason, read on) <BR>4.   Fastest Haste <BR>5.   Tepid Deeds (not shiftless deeds, tepid) <BR>6.   Rune III <BR>7.   Cajoling Whispers <BR>8.   Memblur <P><BR>Notice I use root and tepid deeds instead of better spells. Root casts <BR>in 2.5, immobilize (39th) in 1.8. For this reason, you may choose immobilize,<BR>BUT you will rarely, if ever cast direct damage on a rooted mob. You don't <BR>care if root breaks. Generally, you WANT roots to break quickly. If there <BR>was a 20second sure-hold root, it would be perfect. Also, you'll cast alot of<BR>roots and the mana savings adds up.<P>Tepid slows 50% - shiftless 60%. You will hardly use this spell anyway. You <BR>shouldn't fight too many mobs that pose a challenge to your pet. Tepid is alot<BR>less mana than shiftless. Really not worth it here imho. Generally, <BR>spells 5 and 8 (memblur) are optional. If you wish to put Gate there, <BR>that's a good choice. Another type of root (enstill is longer than root) <BR>for situational use is good too. Also mez if you aren't doing giants. <P>Buffs: The only buffs I keep up are Shielding, CHA buff, and Rune III (and <BR>Clarity duh). Rune 4 is just too dam expensive (10 Rune 3's per Rune 4 <BR>in casting cost). If you are rich, go for 4.  Also, keeping up Troll Illusion <BR>isn't a bad idea if you get hit - the regen is nice. Of course, last but <BR>not least - Sow (or jboots). Buy potions, give druids backrubs, whatever. <BR>Its required. <BR>Shade is ok, but I don't really get hit much. And when I do, Runes eat <BR>it up. Resist magic could be very real, but fighting casters isn't a good <BR>idea anyway. <P>Ok.. Here is my charming scenario levels 43-49. <P>Zone: Eastern Wastes <BR>Important points: Kromrif guards outside Kael can easily be pulled solo. <BR>Just north of Kael is a "dead" zone" there seem to be no wandering <BR>monsters there. Just east of Kael there are tons of wandering blue mobs. <BR>Kromrif guards conned white to me while 43, 44, 45. They seem to vary these <BR>levels. Also, Cajoling Whispers (according to eq.castersrealm.com) charms <BR>only up to 45th level mobs and I never had a problem charming these guards. <P>Medded to full, buffs on as indicated above, spell line up as above. <P>Steps: <BR>1.   Walk down ramp, as far away as possible, tash a guard - run up ramp. <BR>Note that tash is uber important. MR is what seems to matter for broken <BR>charms, not CHA. When my tash spell wears off, I expect a charm break soon <BR>after. <BR>2.   After traveling past top of ramp awhile, turn, wait one sec (so as to <BR>not be spell interrupted) and cast root. <BR>3.   If root is resisted (not often with tash) run north to dead area. <BR>Side slip, run past trees, jump - whatever it takes to gain some ground on the <BR>very upset giant. When you get ample distance, try to reroot (use 3rd <BR>person view camera liberally to check distances). <BR>4.   Once pet is rooted, cast charm. Recast until it sticks. (resists are about 20%<BR>for me I'd estimate).<BR>5.   If root is still holding (likely), approach pet and cast your haste <BR>spell on him (spell range is much smaller than charm). If root is not <BR>holding, head southeast towards mobs. Worry about hasting him once he <BR>is fighting. Since this will be your pet for the next 10-20 minutes, you can <BR>remove the haste spell from your list and replace it with something else if <BR>you like. <BR>6.   If root still holds, go south east and find some prey. Target it and <BR>tash it. Run back to your rooted pet hitting your hotkey "/pet attack" <BR>when near him. Try not to get too close to your rooted pet. Once past pet, <BR>turn and root target near the pet. It is important that during the fight, <BR>you keep the target mob rooted. That way, when charm breaks (not if) you <BR>only have to deal with a free mad pet, not two mad mobs. Also, I did group <BR>some with druids during this. Their snare made recharm a snap but I felt <BR>constrained getting my pets to new locations. However, their tracking is <BR>incredibly useful in finding the next mob. EW is great because there are <BR>LOTS of mobs, a sparser zone would be annoying. Nothing is more frustrating running<BR>a long way with a charmed mob in tow - you know the charm is begging to break.<BR>7.   While pet is fighting target mob, head out of root range and med <BR>watching the battle. Keep your PET targeted (F1 twice) and your fingers on <BR>CTRL-S to stand up. Also your mouse on the root casting icon. Some battles, <BR>your pet will not break charm and you simply get the kill. If he does <BR>break, stand up, root, and recharm. If anything is resisted, start running <BR>and try again. Sometimes, you will lose an almost dead mob because of an <BR>unfortunate charm-break and resists but don't worry about this. Start <BR>working on the next mob, such losses are rare. Also, if the target mob <BR>breaks root during the fight, you can reroot him. If he is almost dead, <BR>don't bother. The best way I've found to reroot is be out of root range and<BR>start madly clicking the root casting "spell gem". Once he enters range, it<BR>will start casting. I tried making a hot key "/sit off" then "/cast 3" but<BR>that meant I had to guess I was in root casting range.. too iffy. <BR>8.   Eventually, you'll have two mad mobs chasing you. If both are giants <BR>(kromrif ex-pet and say a scout) then they are fast runners and you must simply do <BR>some creative rooting to get things under control. Remember, the northwest <BR>area is your friend (just NW of kael entrance), it's a wide open uninhabited area with plenty of room <BR>to root. If the target mob is a manticore or dire wolf, they are slow. <BR>Run awhile, root your ex-pet, then root your target next to him. Even though, <BR>neither is charmed they will fight! They still have each other on their <BR>hate list. If your uncharmed giant kills the target mob ? it will poof! <BR>Don't let that happen if possible, recharm asap. <BR>9.   Once your pet gets hurt enough. Tell him to sit. Then cast invis on <BR>yourself and blast him a few times to get that kill too. There is a nasty <BR>bug that an almost dead mob will warp back to his starting point. This <BR>does happen to these guards and its quite a bother. Blasting my pet is what <BR>really eats mana. A kromrif guard with only a sliver of health still seems <BR>to take a few 44th DD's to bring down. <P>Other topics: <BR>========== <P>Memblurring for xp: <BR>Its said that if a pet does over 50% of the damage, it gets 50% of the <BR>kill. So, you can try to outdamage your pet, but that's horribly mana <BR>inefficient (probably impossible once you see those kromrif guards quading <BR>for 130). Also you could call your pet off an almost dead target and <BR>memblur the old target. Wooly Rhino's start out indiff so on a successful <BR>memblur they go back to indiff. I can attest sometimes it has taken me <BR>4 memblurs to make that happen! I can then blast and (theoretically) get <BR>full xp for the kill. Keep in mind however, the entire time I am casting memblur <BR>(which has a long recast time) my pet is standing right next to me. A charm <BR>break then is deadly. To me, this has become not worth it. I typically <BR>don't personally damage my targets at all. Let the pet do the work and <BR>make up for it in volume. If memblur worked consistently, I might consider <BR>changing my tactics. <P>Note that one kromrif guard has killed up to 14 (fourteen!) xp yielding <BR>mobs for me before being so damaged I needed to retire him. That's in a <BR>span of 10-15 minutes. I then med to full in a few more mins and go get the<BR>other guard!<P>Poofs: <P>Poofs suck. That is, you blast a mob for final kill and it disappears! <BR>No corpse, no xp. This happens because some other (non charmed) mob did more <BR>damage than you and is still alive. Scenarios: <P>1.   Your pet and target mob fight until almost both are completely dead. <BR>Then charm breaks. They both wander off because they are both at a sliver <BR>of health. They have both done 99% damage to each other. If you blast <BR>EITHER, it will poof. If you blast both, the first will poof, the second <BR>will not (because you killed the first who had the most credit for the <BR>kill!). The answer? Recharm your pet, blast the second (or let your pet <BR>kill it), then cast invis and blast your pet. You'll get both kills. <BR>2.   Both your pet and mob are rooted. A moment before the target mob dies, <BR>your pet breaks charm. Because they are rooted next to each other, they <BR>still fight. If the target mob dies then, it poofs. Recharm immediately if <BR>possible. <BR>3.   Your pet fights some mob almost to the death then breaks charm and <BR>chases you. Roots are resisted for awhile. By the time you get your pet <BR>under control, you are halfway across the zone and have no idea where the <BR>original target mob is. One battle later, you blast your own pet and he <BR>poofs. The old target mob (across the zone somewhere) still did more damage <BR>than you and got credit. The only solution here is to memblur your pet <BR>a few times and hope it works. <P>Eventually, you'll lose a nice kill to a poof. Again, its part of the game, <BR>just say "oh poop" and move on. <P>General other rules: <P>Keep Rune up at all times. You are a silly person if you don't. <P>If you are waiting for someone, need to do nothing, whatever - still don't <BR>let your pet near you. Tell him to "/pet sit down" somewhere and stand away <BR>from him. Or just keep running with him chasing far behind. <P>Slowing mobs is not too important. You can, but if your undercon charmed <BR>pet is adequate it doesn't matter much. The final goal is have a pet that <BR>has a SLIVER of health left and kills as many mobs as he can before then. I <BR>slow manticores against my kromrif pet because they really do alot of damage. <BR>If you are full mana during mid-battle (often) then feel free. Full mana is wasted mana. <P>The 35-43 game: <BR>-------------------- <P>This just changes your spells and location. Also your tactics slightly. <BR>First off, change Cajoling Whispers for Beguile. Your DD is weaker but <BR>that isn't too important. You STILL must follow the rule of finding a mean pet <BR>to kill low blues. Iceclad works for this. The two giants standing at the <BR>bridge can kill dire wolves and snow dervish like no tomorrow. <P>The most interesting change is in recharming. A Frost Giant takes about 4 <BR>seconds to get from just inside recharming range to splattering you across <BR>the snow. Beguile takes 3.5 to cast (Cajoling whispers 4.5). If you <BR>sufficiently outrun a mad ex-pet, can just rapidly click the Beguile spell <BR>until it starts casting and get the recharm intact just before he reaches <BR>you. It saves a lot of trouble in re-rooting. The bad news is that it truly <BR>does take you to the edge of do-ability. If the charm resists, you will <BR>likely get hit once or twice. <P>Possible charming zones: <P>+Levels 20-30: Griffins in the Karanas are a known undercon. You can charm <BR>a green griffin and do some fine damage with it. Karana's have nice dead <BR>zones hear the south water (don't get too close to guards) <BR>+Levels 35-40: Iceclad giants at bridge are nice pets. Plenty of dead zone <BR>near bridge and by water <BR>+Levels 38-45: Frost Giant fort in EW. Berzerkers are good, so is Frost <BR>Giant Captain. Dead zone south (same as "dead zone north" for kael <BR>entrance) <BR>+Levels 43-49: Kael entrance - kromrif guards. Dead zone north of kael <BR>entrance. This is Mecca. These giants can pulverize so many mobs that live<BR>just east.<BR>+Levels: 44+: Burning wood - no wonderful undercon but wasps work. Wurms <BR>are trouble because of their long necks. Dead zone by skyfire zone <BR>entrance. <BR>+Levels 30ish: Overthere: No definitive undercons, but plenty of room. <P><BR>Conclusion: <BR>There you go. Charm-soloing is incredibly profitable in xp. Note that I <BR>rarely loot, I fill up too fast. These rules can be applied to druids too. <BR>They haste their pets BETTER than enchanters and their snare spells makes <BR>recharming a non-event. Wooly Rhino's in EW work well for a 40+ druid. <P>Also, charm soloing is nowhere as near as boring as necro/mage soloing or <BR>root/nuke. It's a dance and you have to get good at it. Don't get attached <BR>to your pet either. He'll want to kill you in a minute or two. Switching <BR>pets midstream is great if the mana is high. Your pet is a walking piece of <BR>experience too. <P>Lastly, I'd just like to say I played a rogue to 50 (my first primary) <BR>and it was 100 times harder than an enchanter. My enchanter at 43 could kill <BR>10 giants in 10 minutes. My 50 rogue couldn't kill one. Sure, sure, <BR>solo'ing is not a measure of power. Then what is? My rogue has died  to a <BR>green that jumped him in the dreadland tunnel. I still see rogues shouting <BR>for groups, post 50, pre 50, etc. This game was built to level a caster and <BR>twink a melee for fun. That's not a horrible thing, I just wish it said <BR>that on the box. <P>Igbert, 49 gnome chanter, Worshipper of Agnost <BR>Igbot, defunct 50 gnome rogue <BR>Rodcet Nife<BR>
</FONT>
