<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Mal,<P>See you need a spell slot for your nuke.  Drop blur--you HAVE to keep the enemy rooted for consistent results anyway, and the ole pet doesn't back off of a rooted mob well anyway.<P>Look at my lineup based on spell <I>type</I> without looking at spell names:<P>Level 19:<BR>Sanity Warp - Kill<BR>Charm - Control<BR>Color Flux - Cover<BR>Root - Hold<BR>Mesmerize - Pause<BR>Languid Pace/Quickness - "Edge"<BR>Tashan - Duration<BR>Swap - Buffs<P>Level 32:<BR>Chaos Flux - Kill<BR>Beguile - Control<BR>Color Shift - Cover<BR>Root - Hold<BR>Mesmerize - Pause<BR>Tepid Deeds/Feedback/Alacrity - "Edge"<BR>Tashani - Duration<BR>Swap - Buffs<P>Level 44<BR>Discordant Mind - Kill<BR>Cajoling Whispers/Beguile - Control<BR>Color Shift - Cover<BR>Root - Hold<BR>Mesmerize - Pause<BR>Shiftless Deeds/Feedback/Celerity - "Edge"<BR>Tashania - Duration<BR>Swap - Buffs<P>Level 51 (current for me)<BR>Discordant Mind - Nuke<BR>Allure - Control<BR>Color Skew - Cover<BR>Root - Hold<BR>Mesmerize - Pause<BR>Shiftless Deeds/Feedback/Swift Like the Wind - "Edge"<BR>Tashania - Duration<BR>Swap - Buffs<P>Kill, Control, Cover, Hold, Pause, "Edge", Duration, Buffs.<P>I don't mem both stuns because I'm using an attack slow.  A mob with a slowed attack rate isn't just crippled for your pet, it's crippled in the event it rushes you.  I like the attack slow (good point was raised, it's a large chunk of extra mana) because the worst case scenario has much less impact with attack slows in play.  Look at the three most used "edges" (4th place goes to DOTing/Nuking--but don't EVER DOT when solo--you will regret when you can't mez, or accidentally charm the DOTed one).<P>I take two mobs attacking on a delay of 30, swinging every 3 seconds.  Let's assume they are same level, so will roughly take each other down at the same rate.  These mobs will likely take each other to nearly nothing.  That means you get one fight out of your pet, and unless you try to do some very messy blurring, 1.5 mobs of xp in the end, minimal mana usage.  (Without "edge".)<P>Adding "edge" at level 50 (for really raunchy haste levels) we have:<P>Swift Like the Wind:<BR>60% haste, changing the pets swing time to 1.875 seconds apart.  Now the pet will have 32 combat tics to every 20 tics of the enemy.  Very very impressive.  When charm breaks (not if) you will have 1.125 LESS seconds between combat tics to deal with the mob.  Haste will make the mob MORE deadly to you, and in the "worst case" scenario, you are in deep kaka.  SoW/JBoots makes hasting viable, as you just run away, but Haste is suicide without SoW (stay tuned for more on this mention).  Haste usually lets your pet nail 2 mobs, then give itself for your xp pool... 2 mobs of xp, minimal mana usage.  (Bear in mind still that undercons only live in select places... I'm looking at the run of the mill "make me Jabober" mobs)<P>Feedback:<BR>11pt damage shield on the mob.  As the mobs are going to beating the snot out of each other, the enemy will take an additional 11 damage per hit it scores.  Assuming both mobs score even hits (not a stretch) then assume after every 20 tics, with double-attacking mobs, if half the blows land, that's 220 extra damage.  Very impressive--at 29th.  Seeing as most mobs only double hit without two weapons though... it's still about 220 extra damage at 50th.  Not so impressive, and it will help, but not likely your pet kill more than 2 mobs.  Worst case scenario, two mobs swinging at you at normal rate.  Still full xp for pet, two half xp kills, 2 full xp equivalent.<P>Shiftless Deeds (my choice):<BR>Slow at 50th:  (5% + Level) = 55% slow, so our 3 second delay becomes 6.67 seconds.  Now for every 20 combat tics for our pet, the enemy has 9.  (By the way, Tepid Deeds at 50th... (20% + Level/2) = 45% slow or 4.62 second combat tic--13 tics per 20.)  Anyway, the pet doesn't have an "edge" it's got a rigged fight.  Vs a similar mob, it will SLAUGHTER it.  Vs a weaker one it will emerge nearly unscathed.  Vs a tougher one, it can often drop it, but you might need to drop a nuke in assistance.  But just looking at the combat tics, if your pet needs 20 combat tics to drop the mob (1 minute of combat--pretty realistic guess), then it is answered by 9 attack tics.  Less than half it's life if they are shelling out about the same damage.  Counting it's healing time, you can drop 3 mobs in a row consistently.  That's 2.5 mobs of xp per pet charmed.  And the question most important to me:  Worst case scenario--my normal speed pet, and a mob that swings every 6.7 seconds!  I can almost ignore it!  THIS is my lure to slows... it trivializes the worst case scenario into something MUCH easier to manage.<P>Mana cost?<BR>Haste - 250 mana at charm start.<BR>Feedback - 75 mana per fight, 150 usually.<BR>Shiftless Deeds - 200 mana per fight, 600 usually.<P>Haste DOES use very little mana in the long run... one cast for however many mobs the pet survives.  Mana comes back faster than hit points though... keep that in mind.<P>Feedback is next to nothing still... you gain it back during the fight STANDING with Clarity.<P>Shiftless Deeds is a monster resource hog, but even Tepid Deeds is crippling, and only 100 mana.  But 4.5 seconds vs 6.7 seconds on the attack tic... over TWO extra seconds!?  I didn't even have to think about it.  You will see more mana usage.  But honestly you just med during fights.  That's what you do--and 230 mana per fight (Root and Slow) isn't that hard to regain.  Your mana drops at charm time, not during the fight.<P>Xornn's "edge" explained.   <IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/eq/smile.gif"><P>All three methods work good... and if you really want the necros/mages to weep, hell yes, find a mob that will dual wield, give it SLtW, and proceed to DESTROY everything.  Just remember who buffed the **** out of that thing when it rushes you.<P>Xornn
</FONT>
