<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Eugee, heres some reasoning behind my spell lineup:<P>Tash and beguile are understandable.<BR>If I want to control either the target or my pet I want to root and blur.<BR>I root because its very fast and can keep either former pet or target in one place.<BR>Blur is one of my favorite spells in the game.  If my pet no longer likes me:<BR>Root, back away, blur.  He is outta aggro range.  If my pet dies same thing happens to target.  <BR>At the end of a fight, I blur nuke.  You did give me some advice a while ago about the ineffectiveness of blur/nuke.  Being that between the ungreying of spells and the cast time of anarchy my pet may out damage me.  Given my current level I dont think that will happen (35th), since mobs just arent that fast yet.<BR>I didnt save a slot for DD because after I cast either feedback or tepid I will want to sit and med until both are near dead.  Plenty of time to rememorize a spell.  I also dont want to cast the DD more than once, and then at the end of an encounter, so both feedback and DD are one cast spells most likely.<BR>I didnt put in Mez, which I normally wouldnt go without, because I know I need to root the mob, and once hes rooted im either recasting beguile (should it be a charmbreaking incident) or my pet is already wailing on him.  I may need to reconsider this, and then I would take out the Colorshift in place of it.  I just like having the backup stun, should one get interrupted or fizzle. I am also leaning towards feedback over tepid.  I know that I will cast the feedback once an encounter on my pet.  Tepid will most likely be cast on the enemy, but if my pet breaks, hes wont be slowed, and I want to make sure I can get off a root in time.  Root will tend to hold long enough to blur, and should the blur not work I should be far enough away to recast root.  Have to try out this theory myself, hehe.<BR>Mal<BR>
