<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<B> One thing I have considered trying is casting feedback on both my pet and the MOB he is fighting. This would seem to me to stack well with the tactic of quickening both.<BR>Has anyone ever tried this? Am I out of my mind and there is an obvious reason why it won't work? </B><P>You mean aside from the fact that you cannot fire shield a non charmed mob?  Imagine the abuse and frustration a high lvl magician could do in newbie areas =)<P>*Shudders at the thought of a rat with a 50 pts. damage shield.<P>Works wonderful on your pet though and is something I use alot, since you as the charmer will never melee the mob, and thus not take damage from the buff.  Others haste their pets or slow the target, the first of which can get dangerous if charm breaks ill timed but has the potential to last through several fights.<P>As a rule of thumb I use the following means of buffing/de buffing while charm soloing:<P>"One on One"  This is where you charm fight two tough and somewhat equal mobs.  To have my charmed pet gain the advantage I either slow the target or Feedback my pet.  Slowing becomes much more powerful as you level.<P>"The Lawnmower"  In areas where you can find under cons, ie. mobs that con below their actual combat abilities, and heaps of low blues, I'll often hit my pet with my best haste and have him mow through 5 to 6 blue cons before dispatching myself.<P>When/if you are above 40 and below 50 I suggest going to EW and charm a Whooly Rhino.  Buff it to the teeth and go to work on the orc or giant fort.  <P>That should open your eyes to the "Lawnmower" strategy =)<P>Zeeta<BR>Bristlebane<P><BR>
</FONT>
